==English==
{{wikipedia}}
===Etymology===
Origin uncertain (see discussion page); probably of Romany origin.  Compare Romany ''[[chavi]]'' ‘male child’, ''[[chavo]]'' ‘female child’, ''[[chal]]'' ‘boy’, ''[[chavvy]]'' ‘mate, friend’; see also ''[[charva]]''.

In modern [[Spanish]] the word ''chaval'' is translated as ''lad''.  ''Chavala'' is girl or lass.  This word is in common usage in Spain [http://education.yahoo.com/reference/dict_en_es/spanish/chaval;_ylt=AlXQu4Ue10guDV7rC5VoYwL_s8sF]

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/ʧæv/}}, {{SAMPA|/tS{v/}}
*:Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-æv|-æv]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{italbrac|British|derogatory|informal}} A working-class youth: especially as associated with aggression, poor education, and a perceived "common" taste in clothing and lifestyle.
#{{rfv-sense}} {{italbrac|British|friendly|informal}} Somebody who regularly dresses in casual sports clothing, has a taste for dance and pop music, and is able to talk to younger people on informal terms.

